document.title: Arizona College and Career Ready Standards – Mathematics

D52F6520DFE30131531068A86D17958E.description: (+) Prove the addition and subtraction formulas for sine, cosine, and tangent and use them to solve problems.

D52F0480DFE30131530F68A86D17958E.description: Prove the Pythagorean identity sin²(θ) + cos²(θ) = 1 and use it to find sin(θ), cos(θ), or tan(θ) given sin(θ), cos(θ), or tan(θ) and the quadrant of the angle.

D52E2760DFE30131530D68A86D17958E.description: (+) Use inverse functions to solve trigonometric equations that arise in modeling contexts; evaluate the solutions using technology, and interpret them in terms of the context.

D52DC520DFE30131530C68A86D17958E.description: (+) Understand that restricting a trigonometric function to a domain on which it is always increasing or always decreasing allows its inverse to be constructed.

comments: Modeling is best interpreted not as a collection of isolated topics but in relation to other standards. Making mathematical models is a Standard for Mathematical Practice, and specific modeling standards appear throughout the high school standards indicated by a star symbol (★). The star symbol sometimes appears on the heading for a group of standards; in that case, it should be understood to apply to all standards in that group.
D52D3C80DFE30131530B68A86D17958E.description: Choose trigonometric functions to model periodic phenomena with specified amplitude, frequency, and midline.

D52CE760DFE30131530A68A86D17958E.description: Model periodic phenomena with trigonometric functions

D52C9680DFE30131530968A86D17958E.description: (+) Use the unit circle to explain symmetry (odd and even) and periodicity of trigonometric functions.

D52C4060DFE30131530868A86D17958E.description: (+) Use special triangles to determine geometrically the values of sine, cosine, tangent for π/3, π/4 and π/6, and use the unit circle to express the values of sine, cosine, and tangent for π-x, π+x, and 2π-x in terms of their values for x, where x is any real number.

D52BEA40DFE30131530768A86D17958E.description: Explain how the unit circle in the coordinate plane enables the extension of trigonometric functions to all real numbers, interpreted as radian measures of angles traversed counterclockwise around the unit circle.

D52B8D40DFE30131530668A86D17958E.description: Understand radian measure of an angle as the length of the arc on the unit circle subtended by the angle.

D52B2310DFE30131530568A86D17958E.description: Extend the domain of trigonometric functions using the unit circle

D52A7740DFE30131530368A86D17958E.description: Interpret the parameters in a linear or exponential function in terms of a context.

D52A1FC0DFE30131530268A86D17958E.description: Interpret expressions for functions in terms of the situation they model

D529B4F0DFE30131530168A86D17958E.description: For exponential models, express as a logarithm the solution to ab<sup>ct</sup> = d where a, c, and d are numbers and the base b is 2, 10, or e; evaluate the logarithm using technology.

D5293840DFE30131530068A86D17958E.description: Observe using graphs and tables that a quantity increasing exponentially eventually exceeds a quantity increasing linearly, quadratically, or (more generally) as a polynomial function.

D528D910DFE3013152FF68A86D17958E.description: Construct linear and exponential functions, including arithmetic and geometric sequences, given a graph, a description of a relationship, or two input-output pairs (include reading these from a table).

D5287FE0DFE3013152FE68A86D17958E.description: Recognize situations in which a quantity grows or decays by a constant percent rate per unit interval relative to another.

D5281300DFE3013152FD68A86D17958E.description: Recognize situations in which one quantity changes at a constant rate per unit interval relative to another.

D52781E0DFE3013152FC68A86D17958E.description: Prove that linear functions grow by equal differences over equal intervals, and that exponential functions grow by equal factors over equal intervals.

D5272960DFE3013152FB68A86D17958E.description: Distinguish between situations that can be modeled with linear functions and with exponential functions.

D526D020DFE3013152FA68A86D17958E.description: Construct and compare linear, quadratic, and exponential models and solve problems

comments: Modeling is best interpreted not as a collection of isolated topics but in relation to other standards. Making mathematical models is a Standard for Mathematical Practice, and specific modeling standards appear throughout the high school standards indicated by a star symbol (★). The star symbol sometimes appears on the heading for a group of standards; in that case, it should be understood to apply to all standards in that group.

D52613D0DFE3013152F868A86D17958E.description: (+) Understand the inverse relationship between exponents and logarithms and use this relationship to solve problems involving logarithms and exponents.

D525ADD0DFE3013152F768A86D17958E.description: (+) Produce an invertible function from a non-invertible function by restricting the domain.

D52552F0DFE3013152F668A86D17958E.description: (+) Read values of an inverse function from a graph or a table, given that the function has an inverse.

D524F6D0DFE3013152F568A86D17958E.description: (+) Verify by composition that one function is the inverse of another.

D5249050DFE3013152F468A86D17958E.description: Solve an equation of the form f(x) = c for a simple function f that has an inverse and write an expression for the inverse.
comments: For example, f(x) =2 x3 or f(x) = (x+1)/(x—1) for x ? 1.

D523B750DFE3013152F268A86D17958E.description: Identify the effect on the graph of replacing f(x) by f(x) + k, k f(x), f(kx), and f(x + k) for specific values of k (both positive and negative); find the value of k given the graphs. Experiment with cases and illustrate an explanation of the effects on the graph using technology. Include recognizing even and odd functions from their graphs and algebraic expressions for them.

D52360D0DFE3013152F168A86D17958E.description: Build new functions from existing functions

comments: Modeling is best interpreted not as a collection of isolated topics but in relation to other standards. Making mathematical models is a Standard for Mathematical Practice, and specific modeling standards appear throughout the high school standards indicated by a star symbol (★). The star symbol sometimes appears on the heading for a group of standards; in that case, it should be understood to apply to all standards in that group.
D52300D0DFE3013152F068A86D17958E.description: Write arithmetic and geometric sequences both recursively and with an explicit formula, use them to model situations, and translate between the two forms.

comments: For example, build a function that models the temperature of a cooling body by adding a constant function to a decaying exponential, and relate these functions to the model.
D52239C0DFE3013152EE68A86D17958E.description: Combine standard function types using arithmetic operations.

comments: For example, if T(y) is the temperature in the atmosphere as a function of height, and h(t) is the height of a weather balloon as a function of time, then T(h(t)) is the temperature at the location of the weather balloon as a function of time.

D52197B0DFE3013152ED68A86D17958E.description: Determine an explicit expression, a recursive process, or steps for calculation from a context.

comments: Modeling is best interpreted not as a collection of isolated topics but in relation to other standards. Making mathematical models is a Standard for Mathematical Practice, and specific modeling standards appear throughout the high school standards indicated by a star symbol (★). The star symbol sometimes appears on the heading for a group of standards; in that case, it should be understood to apply to all standards in that group.
D5213D50DFE3013152EC68A86D17958E.description: Write a function that describes a relationship between two quantities

D520E550DFE3013152EB68A86D17958E.description: Build a function that models a relationship between two quantities

D5202860DFE3013152E968A86D17958E.description: Compare properties of two functions each represented in a different way (algebraically, graphically, numerically in tables, or by verbal descriptions).
comments: For example, given a graph of one quadratic function and an algebraic expression for another, say which has the larger maximum.

For example, identify percent rate of change in functions such as y = (1.02)<sup>t</sup>, y = (0.97)<sup>t</sup>, y = (1.01 <sup>12t</sup>, y = (1.2)<sup>t/10</sup>, and classify them as representing exponential growth or decay.
D51FC520DFE3013152E868A86D17958E.description: Use the properties of exponents to interpret expressions for exponential functions.

D51F62D0DFE3013152E768A86D17958E.description: Use the process of factoring and completing the square in a quadratic function to show zeros, extreme values, and symmetry of the graph, and interpret these in terms of a context.

D51EFD80DFE3013152E668A86D17958E.description: Write a function defined by an expression in different but equivalent forms to reveal and explain different properties of the function.

D51EA440DFE3013152E568A86D17958E.description: Graph exponential and logarithmic functions, showing intercepts and end behavior, and trigonometric functions, showing period, midline, and amplitude.

D51E4960DFE3013152E468A86D17958E.description: (+) Graph rational functions, identifying zeros and asymptotes when suitable factorizations are available, and showing end behavior.

D51DE220DFE3013152E368A86D17958E.description: Graph polynomial functions, identifying zeros when suitable factorizations are available, and showing end behavior.

D51D8B50DFE3013152E268A86D17958E.description: Graph square root, cube root, and piecewise-defined functions, including step functions and absolute value functions.

D51D3210DFE3013152E168A86D17958E.description: Graph linear and quadratic functions and show intercepts, maxima, and minima.

D51CD320DFE3013152E068A86D17958E.description: Graph functions expressed symbolically and show key features of the graph, by hand in simple cases and using technology for more complicated cases.

D51BE800DFE3013152DE68A86D17958E.description: Calculate and interpret the average rate of change of a function (presented symbolically or as a table) over a specified interval. Estimate the rate of change from a graph.

D51B89C0DFE3013152DD68A86D17958E.description: Relate the domain of a function to its graph and, where applicable, to the quantitative relationship it describes.

D51B2850DFE3013152DC68A86D17958E.description: For a function that models a relationship between two quantities, interpret key features of graphs and tables in terms of the quantities, and sketch graphs showing key features given a verbal description of the relationship.
comments: Key features include: intercepts; intervals where the function is increasing, decreasing, positive, or negative; relative maximums and minimums; symmetries; end behavior; and periodicity.

D51AD070DFE3013152DB68A86D17958E.description: Interpret functions that arise in applications in terms of the context

D51A7230DFE3013152DA68A86D17958E.description: Recognize that sequences are functions, sometimes defined recursively, whose domain is a subset of the integers.
comments: For example, the Fibonacci sequence is defined recursively by f(0) = f(1) = 1, f(n+1) = f(n) + f(n-1) for n ≥ 1.

D51A1070DFE3013152D968A86D17958E.description: Use function notation, evaluate functions for inputs in their domains, and interpret statements that use function notation in terms of a context.

D519BCB0DFE3013152D868A86D17958E.description: Understand that a function from one set (called the domain) to another set (called the range) assigns to each element of the domain exactly one element of the range. If f is a function and x is an element of its domain, then f(x) denotes the output of f corresponding to the input x. The graph of f is the graph of the equation y = f(x).

D51967F0DFE3013152D768A86D17958E.description: Understand the concept of a function and use function notation

E1E6681FC3634524913B43A4CFED5456.description: Look for and express regularity in repeated reasoning.

83314C345580452091F5F703BF216CA0.description: Look for and make use of structure.

AAF1F6FBC605475B849A79D7B8D68330.description: Construct viable arguments and critique the reasoning of others.

22D77F5ABB3C4428B0364A6F0A89F72B.description: Make sense of problems and persevere in solving them.
